= @PROJECT_NAME@(1)

== Name

@PROJECT_NAME@ - set the per-user VNC password for pam_fnal_vncpasswd

== Synopsis

*@PROJECT_NAME@* [*-h* | *--help*] [*--version*]

== Description

*@PROJECT_NAME@* sets the per-user VNC password authenticated by
*pam_fnal_vncpasswd*(8).  It prompts for a new password twice on the
controlling terminal, hashes it using the system's preferred *crypt*(3)
algorithm (yescrypt on RHEL 9+ with libxcrypt >= 4.4), and writes the hash
atomically to *~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/@VNC_PASSWD_FILENAME@*.

The tool acts on behalf of the calling process's real UID.  It does not
require elevated privileges and must not be installed setuid.

== Options

*-h*, *--help*::
  Print a short usage summary including the password file path and exit.

*--version*::
  Print the program name and version string and exit.

== Password Requirements

Passwords must be between *@VNC_MIN_PASSWORD_LENGTH@* and *8* characters.
The upper bound is fixed by the RFB protocol and cannot be changed.
The tool enforces both limits before hashing.  No other character-class
policy is applied; the quality of the chosen password is the user's
responsibility.

The length upper bound also functions as a denial-of-service guard: the PAM
module imposes no length check on authentication because a password too long
to have been set by this tool will produce a mismatched hash and fail
naturally.

== Security

=== Algorithm and Salt

Salt generation uses *getrandom*(2) — the kernel CSPRNG — in a loop that
tolerates short reads before the entropy pool is fully seeded.  The salt is
passed to *crypt_gensalt_ra*(3) with a NULL prefix (compiled-in preferred
algorithm) and count 0 (algorithm default cost).

This may cause a hang on systems with an unseeded entropy pool.

=== Atomic Write

The password file is written as follows to prevent partial-write corruption:

. *mkostemp*(3) creates a temporary file in the same directory as the
  destination, with *O_CLOEXEC* set.
. *fchmod*(2) sets permissions to *0600* before any data is written.
. *write*(2) writes the hash followed by a newline.  An incomplete write is treated as *EIO*.
. *fsync*(2) flushes the data to stable storage.
. *rename*(2) atomically replaces the destination.
. When built with SELinux support, *selinux_restorecon*(3) is called on the
  destination path; failure is non-fatal.

Atomic file writes are not guaranteed on network filesystems.

=== Terminal I/O

Passwords are read via *readpassphrase*(3bsd) with *RPP_ECHO_OFF* and
*RPP_REQUIRE_TTY*.  The tool fails if no controlling terminal is available
rather than reading silently from stdin.

== Password File

----
~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/@VNC_PASSWD_FILENAME@
----

A single line containing a *crypt*(3) hash.  The VNC configuration directory
(*~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@*) is created with mode *0700* if it does not already
exist.

The PAM module (*pam_fnal_vncpasswd*(8)) validates that this file is owned
by the user, is a regular file (not a symlink), and has no executable or
group/world read-write bits set.  Files not satisfying those requirements
will cause authentication to fail with *PAM_AUTHINFO_UNAVAIL*.

== Exit Status

*0*::
  Password updated successfully.

*1*::
  An error occurred: password too short or long, passwords did not match,
  hashing failed, or the password file could not be written.  A diagnostic
  message is printed to standard error.

== Files

*~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/@VNC_PASSWD_FILENAME@*::
  Per-user VNC password file.

*~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/*::
  VNC configuration directory, created mode *0700* if absent.

== See Also

*pam_fnal_vncpasswd*(8), *crypt*(3), *crypt_gensalt_ra*(3),
*readpassphrase*(3bsd), *getrandom*(2), *explicit_bzero*(3)

